@NODE INTRO "Introduction"
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT FEAT
@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}

Spot has always had that annoying empty space on its screen,
and Anthony Brice wanted some nice little buttons to fill it
up.  I did the dirty deeds, but it wasn't terribly good.
Steve Pearson popped up with his new script which had a prefs
file to go with it.

It still wasn't good enough though.  It needed more features,
it needed more configurability, it needed more.

So, I gave it more.  The product, is SpotButtons v2.0.

And it doesn't even need MUI.



SpotButtons requires a registered version of Spot to operate, and KS2.0+
@ENDNODE
@NODE FEAT "Features List"
@PREV INTRO
@NEXT INSTALL
@{fg shine}Features@{fg text}

    *   User-definable buttons, commands, and command types

    *   Versatile styling of the SpotButtons window, including
            -   window title
            -   window position
            -   iconified window position
            -   alteration of background patterns
            -   all window spaces
            -   control over all gadgets (zip/size/close/depth etc.)

    *   Easy to use front-end

    *   Choose between a button interface or a list of items

    *   Fully featured inbuilt preferences section

    *   Automatic iconification when accessing messages in Spot

    *   Groovy scrolling messages ;-)
@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALL "Installation"
@PREV FEAT
@NEXT CONFIG
@{fg shine}Installation@{fg text}

In this archive you should have the files:

    SpotButtons.Spot
    SpotButtons.Guide
    SpotButtons.Doc

    RexxSupport.Library
    Triton.Library
    TritonRexx.Library

If any of these are missing or corrupt in some way, please advise
both the author and the source of your archive.

Installation of SpotButtons is simple.  Copy the file "SpotButtons.Spot"
to the place where you store all your Spot scripts (typically Rexx:Spot/).

Now copy the three .library files into LIBS: unless you already have them
installed.  These libraries are vital to the working of SpotButtons,
so don't come complaining to me about why it asks for a library when you
start it. :-)

Important: If you have installed a previous version of SpotButtons,
you will need to erase the previous configuration file since it is
incompatible with this new enhanced version.
SpotButtons will seek for it in Mail:SpotButtons.Cfg

Now you can run the script from Spot's "Rexx/Execute Script..." menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CONFIG "Configuration"
@PREV INSTALL
@NEXT USAGE
@{fg shine}Configuration@{fg text}

The whole idea behind SpotButtons is configurability.  There is little point
to it if you can't design it to suit your own system.

Once you have installed SpotButtons, run it from Spot's "Rexx/Execute Script..."
menu.

If all goes well, a small window should appear in the top-left of your Spot
screen, with one button named "Preferences" inside it.  Since you have not
configured anything yet, there is nothing to see!  Click on the Preferences button
now.

With any luck, a new window should appear in the centre of the screen.  The Save
button save the preferences into the configuration file (Mail:SpotButtons.Cfg
unless another has been specified), while Cancel will close the Preferences window
without altering the configuration file.

The other 4 buttons: General; Spacing; Gadgets; Buttons, all open new windows as
explained below.


@{b}General@{ub}

A group of miscellanous options which do not fit under any specific category :

         Title - the text to be displayed in the title of the window
 Left Position - left coordinate of the window
  Top Position - top coordinate of the window
Left Iconified - left iconified coordinate of the window
 Top Iconified - top iconified coordinate of the window
        Format - select between viewing items as buttons or in a list
        Fill 1 - Fill 1/2 allow different coloured
        Fill 2 - backgrounds to be created in the window


@{b}Spacing@{ub}

This section has 5 cycle gadgets, all of which perform the same function.
They are included so that the user has more control over the spacing between
the buttons and the border of the window, and between the buttons themselves.

     Top - the space between the title bar and the first button
    Left - the space between the left of the window and the buttons
  Bottom - the space between the bottom of the window and the last button
   Right - the space between the right of the window and the buttons
Interior - the space between two separate buttons vertically

Each of these gadgets has 4 settings:

    None - no space
   Small - small space (.5 of normal)
  Normal - normal sized space
     Big - large space (2x normal)


@{b}Gadgets@{ub}

This window consists of 8 cycle gadgets.  Each can either be set to "Yes" or "No".

          Zip - does the window have a zip gadget?
         Size - does the window have a size gadget?
        Close - does the window have a close gadget?
        Depth - does the window have a depth gadget?
    Activated - is the window activated on startup?
     Drag Bar - can the window be dragged using the title bar?
Status Window - is there to be a status window?
   Extra Bank - should the "P" and "E" buttons be created?


@{b}Buttons@{ub}

This is the main part of configuring SpotButtons.  The main part of the window
is a list of all the currently configured buttons.

The six buttons below it are self-explanatory.

"Button" is the name which will be displayed in the SpotButtons window.  It has
no effect on the workings of the item launched.

The cycle gadget next to it allows the user to select one of three types of button:

    Rexx - identical to selecting the "Rexx/Execute Script..." menu item in Spot,
           or the "E" button in SpotButtons.  This is used to launch Spot scripts.

     CLI - this can be used to launch normal AmigaDOS commands.  This is especially
           useful for the likes of the Spot programmer who's scripts go haywire -
           the programmer can then create buttons for killing the script/Triton GUI
           and so on.

    Spot - this type is used for launching specific Spot ARexx commands, such as
           'messages', 'iconify', 'beep', and so on.  Again, this is useful for the
           programmer, ie. for 'unlockgui' and 'progress close 1' for crashed scripts.

"Command" is the important part.  For the button to have any action at all, something
must be input into here.  The contents of this depends on the type of button selected.

Examples:

For Rexx - "Rexx:Spot/SpotButtons.Spot"
 For CLI - "Dir C:"
For Spot - "unlockgui"
                            (without double-quotes)

For each type except "Spot", the file requester button can be used to easily select
a script/command to execute.

In each of these windows, "Use" will keep the current settings, while "Cancel"
will restore the previous settings.
@ENDNODE
@NODE USAGE "Using SpotButtons"
@PREV CONFIG
@NEXT BUGS
@{fg shine}Using SpotButtons@{fg text}

There isn't much to know.  Once you've @{"configured" LINK CONFIG} it,
you click on the little buttons, and there you go.

If you call SpotButtons from the CLI, you can provide an argument which
is the location of an alternative configuration file instead of Mail:SpotButtons.Cfg

Eg.

Rexx:Spot/SpotButtons.Spot DH1:Prefs/SpotButtons.1

All the standard options (About, Preferences, Execute Script, Quit) are
available in the Project menu (remember to select the SpotButtons window
first), plus each button you setup is listed in the Items menu.

If you have the "Extra Bank" option selected, there will be two extra
buttons in your window.  The first, "P" calls the preferences section,
while clicking "E" allows you to execute another script.

SpotButtons will also check to see if you are in the Messages section of Spot,
since the button window tends to cover up some of the screen in this section,
and so will iconify itself when necessary.  The location of this new window
can also be configured.

Quitting Spot
-------------

When you attempt to quit Spot with SpotButtons still running, Spot tells you
to close all windows.  This can often become annoying, and so I added another
feature.  SpotButtons will always check to see if Spot is trying to quit, and
if it finds that it is, it will close its windows and exit also.

To implement this, though, you must first edit your _Quit.Spot script to
include the following :

===
/* _Quit.Spot Ammendment For SpotButtons */

Options Results
Address 'SPOT'

If ~Show(L,'rexxsupport.library') Then Do
    If ~Addlib('rexxsupport.library',10,-30,0) Then Do
        Say "Error : Please install the rexxsupport.library in LIBS:"
        Call CleanUp
    End
End

Call SetClip("STI","QUIT")
Call Delay(50)
'QuitSpot'

Exit
===

(you may also apply this to _Iconify.Spot, remembering to alter the 'QuitSpot' line)

This will send a message to SpotButtons, telling it that Spot wishes to close down,
and SpotButtons will respond by shutting all its windows and exiting.

Hopefully this will become standard with all scripts which use the Triton interface
with Spot.  (STI standards for Spot-Triton-Interactivity, BTW)
@ENDNODE
@NODE BUGS "Bugs"
@PREV USAGE
@NEXT TODO
@{fg shine}Known Bugs@{fg text}

    *   The Fill 1/2 colour palettes in the General preferences
        menu encounter some "problems" with screens with more
        than 2 bitplanes (ie. >4 colours).  The problem is that
        TritonRexx windows can only consist of the first 4 colours
        of the screen.  However, TritonRexx palettes will display
        all of the colours available on a screen.  This means that
        while you can select colours 4 onwards, SpotButtons has
        to degrade them to the first 4 colours in order to work.
        This is not a bug in SpotButtons, but a restriction in
        TritonRexx in order to ease the implementation of
        backgrounds.

    *   If the "Size Gadget" is set to Yes and the Zip gadget
        is set to No, both gadgets will still appear.
        I assume this is either due to Intuition or TritonRexx
        requiring both of them to be active?

@ENDNODE
